metadata.name: Ceremony #99
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I‚Äôm so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. ü•Ç

Definitely check out ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode by tapping ‚ÄúF‚Äù or mouse click/tap ‚Äî it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will ‚Äúnever forget‚Äù and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that‚Äôs a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses ‚Äú‚Ä¶Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.‚Äù Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: The Spectrum Of Nature #165
metadata.description:
*\_../*`¬¨-‚Äô\/*`¬¨‚Äô‚Äô¬¨`*\/‚Äô-¬¨`*\.._/*

Nature, nature, evolving might‚Ä¶ Silent inventor, always right.
Where is the edge of nature and where do we begin?  
What is of nature and what is of man? 
Isn't everything made by nature's hands?

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article ‚ÄúThe spectrum of nature - a short making of‚Äù. Link at the bottom. If you‚Äôd rather just ignore my personal meaning, feel free to skip the article. 

\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\

Basic info:
The piece comes in possible portrait or landscape versions. Both have a relative size of 1 by 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high for portrait. And 1500x1000 for landscape. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that‚Äôs present. 

../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\..

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. A box will pop up in the top left saying ‚Äúdone‚Äù for 4 seconds when it‚Äôs ready. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won‚Äôt need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there. 

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however. 

/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: NOMADS #9
metadata.description:
NOMADS tells a story through each of its editions: the migration of a population, following simple rules, and whose movements reveal complex shapes and textures, both visual and auditory.
Movement, order, chaos, borders, convergence, wandering, rotation... it's all part of NOMADS

Enjoy the journey as much as the destination


KEYBOARD SHORCUTS:
[S]: Redraw the art and save a 4K PNG
[L]: Toggle between "Infinite Loop" and "Single Render" modes
[M]: Toggle mute

MOUSE / TOUCHSCREEN:
[Click / Tap]: Toggle mute
[Double Click / Double Tap]: Save the current render

URL PARAMETERS:
?start : bypass the intro timer and start the rendering
?loop : select the "Infinite Loop" mode by default
?resolution=1920x1080 : render in a custom resolution using the format WIDTHxHEIGHT. Different aspect ratios will produce different results.
?frame=0.1 : control the frame size around the canvas (value between 0 and 1)
?save : automatically save the image when the rendering is done


Artist: Estienne
Oct. 2022
NFT 2.0 License

Best viewed on Chrome or Chromium based browser
Tested on Chrome v 106.0.5249.119

Libraries used:
p5.js
Tone.js

metadata.name: Unfolded #96
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #71
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: The Passing of Time #117
metadata.description:
To celebrate the one-year anniversary of fx(hash), an animated piece that both signifies and illustrates the passing of time. The generative code is derived from Before/After, but adds a unique animation algorithm that causes the artwork to organically expand and contract. The art adapts to different screen sizes but will work best in full-screen mode on a wide-screen monitor.

The Passing of Time is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive t-SNE transformation implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used.

<space bar>: Pause the animation.
0, 1, 2, 3, 4: Resolution, from lowest (0) to highest (4); default is 2. Try to lower the resolution if the animation isn't smooth.

50% of primary proceeds will be donated to Tezos Ukraine, https://donate.tezos.org.ua/.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Sedimentary Dissolution #5
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the geological processes related to sedimentary dissolution. Dissolution is a form of weathering which contributes to the creation of new rocks. In this piece, various algorithms take on the role of dissolution, producing visual recombinations of the original "sedimentary rock".

Instructions ::

p : save a hi-res image
e : toggle erosion on and off
s : toggle structure on and off
a : toggle all effects on and off

If offset, rgb dissolution or cross-bedding is true you can toggle it on and off.
If these features are false pressing the key will have no effect.

o : toggle offset on and off
r : toggle rgb dissolution on and off
c : toggle cross-bedding on and off

There are 20 versions you can explore, all using the same features.
Use the left and right arrow to change the random seed. 
Pressing space will re-instantiate the original random seed.

metadata.name: Slanted #32
metadata.description:
Fun little game, simple rules:
- start with a randomly sized grid
- pick 2 random cells
- recursively, every cell draw itself
- then it picks two of its neighbors for the next step

Some cells are drawn multiple times, some others are never picked up, but the process it's not completely random.

metadata.name: Offset Disorder #79
metadata.description:
This work is an experiment using generated risograph halftones and hand-drawn elements to create a highly textured pattern. 

- Viewing in Chrome is recommended.
- Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. 
- Image size is 1200x1200px.

Common Features:
- Random 3 to 10 color palette using colors from p5riso
- Individual color layer shifts from 2 to 20px
- Simplex or square color noise patters
- Glitches resulting in hand-drawn shapes
- Glitch rate of 10-50% of shapes

Less Common
- Linear color distribution (top -> bottom)
- Up to 5 large hand-drawn circles
- Very high glitch rate of 50%

Rare
- Perfect color alignment with no errors

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Dencity #100
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Caustics #91
metadata.description:
Domain warped noise and circles simulating the caustic effects of light through a column of water. The pattern is rendered by two passes of variable poisson sampling.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 5,000 px.

Common Features:
- 40+ color palettes
- 50/50 color or black and white
- If color, 50/50 full color or mono + right color palette
- Dark or light background
- Variable number of bubbles
- Variable spacing between bubbles
- Pattern intensity through bubbles
- Pattern banding

Rare
- 20% dark with duotone palettes of grey + gold, bronze, or blue
